{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"df09d59b-99d5-4015-8f5c-b5906353331f","content":"Yes, you'll hit **framework compatibility issues**. MSTest v3 requires:\n\n- **.NET 6.0+** (for modern .NET)\n- **.NET Framework 4.6.2+**\n\nYour project targets **three frameworks**, and two are problematic:\n\n| Target | MSTest v3 Compatible? |\n|---|---|\n| `net462` | ✅ Yes |\n| `net5.0` | ❌ No — dropped in v3 |\n| `netcoreapp3.1` | ❌ No — dropped in v3 |\n\n**To migrate**, you'd need to update the unsupported targets to supported versions (e.g., `net5.0` → `net6.0` or `net8.0`, `netcoreapp3.1` → `net6.0` or `net8.0`).\n\nAlso note that MSTest v3 consolidates `MSTest.TestFramework` + `MSTest.TestAdapter` into a single **`MSTest`** meta-package, so you can simplify your `<PackageReference>` items. There are also some behavioral changes (e.g., class/assembly cleanup lifecycle defaults), so review the [migration guide](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/core/testing/unit-testing-mstest-migration) before upgrading.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"58a66dc9-46c5-4ef9-9a3f-5700b91b5516","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user has a project that multi-targets `net5.0`, `net462`, and `netcoreapp3.1`. They want to migrate from MSTest v2 (2.2.10) to MSTest v3.\n\nMSTest v3 has some important compatibility changes:\n\n1. **Dropped framework support**: MSTest v3 dropped support for older target frameworks. Specifically:\n   - `.NET 5.0` is no longer supported (it's out of support from Microsoft as well)\n   - `.NET Core 3.1` is no longer supported (also out of support)\n   - `.NET Framework 4.6.2` — MSTest v3 supports .NET Framework 4.6.2+, so this should still work.\n   \nTo be more precise, MSTest v3 requires .NET 6.0 or later for .NET Core/.NET targets, and .NET Framework 4.6.2 or later. So the user will need to update their target frameworks to supported versions like `net6.0` or `net8.0` instead of `net5.0` and `netcoreapp3.1`.\n\nMSTest v3 also consolidates the packages into a single `MSTest` meta-package, though the separate `MSTest.TestFramework` and `MSTest.TestAdapter` packages still exist. There are other breaking changes too—some APIs were removed or changed, default behaviors shifted around class and assembly cleanup, and `TestContext` properties now need to be non-nullable in certain contexts.","outputTokens":793,"requestId":"7C19:175BE3:2BA9E52:30A11C7:69F95A74"},"id":"b50b939d-8a1b-4b65-9d2a-db1a8c4e8c93","timestamp":"2026-05-05T02:48:35.987Z","parentId":"553f9fd3-68b8-466e-b047-c2e6aac12d0f"}
